revision.text:
[[File:Liang Wudi.jpg|thumb|300px|Xiao Yan, ''Martial Emperor of Liang'', ca. 700 AD, [[National Palace Museum]], [[Taipei]].]] Much traditional [[Chinese art]] was made for the imperial court, often to be then redistributed as gifts. As well as [[Chinese painting]], sculpture and [[Chinese calligraphy]], there are a great range of what may be called [[decorative arts|decorative]] or [[applied art]]s. [[Chinese fine art]] is distinguished from [[Chinese folk art]], which differs in its style and purpose. This article gives an overview of the many different applied arts of China.
==Calligraphy== {{main|Chinese calligraphy}}
The Chinese imperial court collected calligraphy pieces from the most skilled calligraphers in the country. The collection contains many masterpieces made by well-known calligraphers throughout Chinese art history. Furthermore, because of calligraphy's high artistic value, calligraphy collecting was popular among several Chinese emperors in multiple dynasties.
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="4"> File:Ouyang Xun Bu Shang Tie.jpg|''Bu Shang Tie'' by [[Ouyang Xun]], [[Palace Museum]], [[Beijing]] File:Crossing the Frozen River.jpg|''Crossing the Frozen River'', a poem in running script by [[Kangxi Emperor]] (1654–1722), [[Palace Museum]], [[Beijing]] File:Calligraphy on fan by Mo Shilong, China, Ming dynasty, 16th century, ink on gold paper, Honolulu Academy of Arts.JPG|Calligraphy on fan by Mo Shilong, China, [[Ming dynasty]], 16th century, ink on gold paper, [[Honolulu Academy of Arts]] File:Su shi-calligraphy.jpg|''The Cold Food Observance'' (detail), ink on paper, by [[Su Shi]], [[National Palace Museum]], [[Taipei]] </gallery>
==Ceramics== {{main|Chinese ceramics}} [[Chinese ceramics]], whose history originates back to the pre-dynastic periods, has continuously improved since then, and it is one of the most significant forms of Chinese art.
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="4"> File:Yellow dragon jar (cropped).JPG|Yellow dragon jar, [[Ming dynasty]]. 1521–1567. [[Palace Museum]], [[Beijing]]. File:Dish with underglazed blue and overglazed red design of clouds and dragons, Jingdezhen ware, Yongzheng reign 1723-1735, Qing, Shanghai Museum.jpg|Dish with underglazed blue and overglazed red design of clouds and dragons, [[Jingdezhen ware]], [[Yongzheng Emperor|Yongzheng period]] (1723–1735), [[Qing dynasty]], [[Shanghai Museum]] File:SancaiHorseTang7-8thCentury.JPG|Sancai glazed ceramic horse, [[Tang dynasty]], 7th–8th century, [[Musée Guimet]] File:Chinese jar, Ming dynasty, Jiajing period (1521-1567), porcelain, HAA.JPG|Chinese jar, [[Ming dynasty]], [[Jiajing Emperor|Jiajing period]] (1521–1567), porcelain, [[Honolulu Academy of Arts]] File:Chinese glazed stoneware jar, Yuan dynasty, HAA.JPG|Chinese glazed stoneware jar, [[Yuan dynasty]], [[Honolulu Academy of Arts]] File:Blue glazed vase with golden medallion design.jpg|blue glazed vase with golden medallion design, [[Jingdezhen ware]]，1875–1908 A.D., a collection of [[Shanghai Museum]] </gallery>
===Snuff bottle=== {{main|Snuff bottle}}
After opium was introduced to China, snuff bottles became popular. The Chinese royalties were addicted to them, as they used opium as a long-life medicine. The design of the snuff bottles flourished because of the money that the rich poured into the industry. Many of these bottles were made by talented artisans using tiny paints brushes; they were painted from inside of the bottle, reaching down from the top of the narrow neck. They are still highly collectible up to this day.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="4"> File:Chinese snuff bottles.jpg|Chinese snuff bottles, various time periods, [[British Museum]] in [[London]]. File:Chinese snuff bottle, 19th century, glass bottle with jadeite stopper, Honolulu Museum of Art II.JPG|Chinese snuff bottle, 19th century, glass bottle with jadeite stopper, [[Honolulu Museum of Art]] </gallery>
