==Lacquer== {{main|Lacquerware#Chinese lacquerware|Carved lacquer}} It was during the [[Shang dynasty]] (c. 1600–1046 BCE) when the sophisticated techniques used in the lacquer process were first developed, and it became a highly artistic craft.<ref name=Webb3>Webb, 2000. p. 3.</ref> Various prehistoric lacquerware have been unearthed in China dating back to the [[Neolithic]] period.<ref name=Webb3/> The earliest extant lacquer object, a red wooden bowl,<ref>Stark, 2005. p. 30.</ref> was unearthed at a Hemudu culture (c. 5000–4500 BCE) site.<ref>Wang, 1982. p. 80.</ref> By the Han dynasty (206 BCE – 220 CE), many centers of lacquer production had become established.<ref name=Webb3/> The knowledge of the Chinese methods focusing on the lacquer process spread from China during the Han, Tang, and Song dynasties. Later on, it was eventually introduced to the rest of the world—Korea, Japan, Southeast and South Asia.<ref>Institute, ed., 1983. p. 211.</ref>
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="4"> File:Dish with Roses LACMA M.2005.57 (1 of 2).jpg|[[Carved lacquer]] tray with roses, [[Yuan dynasty]], 16 cm across File:MS-PerlmuttlackPäoniendose16Jh.JPG|Chinese mother of pearl lacquer box with peony decor, [[Ming dynasty]], 16th century, Museum für Lackkunst, [[Münster]] (Germany) File:Miscellany in the Villa Ephrussi de Rothschild - screen.jpg|[[Coromandel lacquer]] screen with figures in pavilions and a main border with a "hundred antiques". File:FFM-QingRotlackDose.JPG|Chinese lacquerware box from the [[Qing dynasty]], [[Museum für angewandte Kunst Frankfurt|Museum für angewandte Kunst]], [[Frankfurt]], [[Germany]] </gallery>
