===Ivory carving=== {{main|Ivory carving}}
Ivory was not a prestigious material in the rather strict hierarchy of Chinese art, where [[jade]] had always been far more highly regarded, and rhinoceros horn (which was not ivory) had a special auspicious meaning.<ref>Rawson, 179–182.</ref> But ivory, as well as bone, had been used for various items since early times when China still had its own species of elephant. Demand for ivory seems to have played a large part in their extinction, which came before 100 BC. During the [[Ming dynasty]], ivory began to be used for small statuettes of gods and others (see gallery). In the Qing dynasty, it suited the growing taste for intricate carving and became more prominently used for brush-holders, boxes, handles and similar pieces. Later on, Canton even developed large models of houses and other large and showy pieces, which remained popular.<ref>Rawson, 182.</ref> Enormous examples are still seen as decorative centrepieces at government receptions. Figures were typically uncoloured, or just with certain features coloured in ink which was often just black, but sometimes a few other colors.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="4"> File:WenChang-MingDynasty-ROM-May8-08.png|Ivory figurine of [[Wen Chang]], the "God of Literature". Circa 1550–1644, [[Ming dynasty]], [[Royal Ontario Museum]]. <!-- Deleted image removed: File:Chinese ivory carving.jpg|1900's Chinese ivory sculpture. The globe at the top has 54 independently rotating layers. --> File:Romance of the Western Chamber fans Asian Art Museum SF 1992.93.1-2.JPG|A pair of ivory fans depicting scenes from [[Romance of the Western Chamber]], c. 1800–1911, [[Qing dynasty]]. On display at the [[Asian Art Museum of San Francisco|Asian Art Museum]] in [[San Francisco]], [[California]]. File:Ivory table screen, Qianlong reign period.JPG|A Chinese ivory table screen with carved decoration of an outdoor scene, from the [[Qing dynasty]], dated to the reign of the [[Qianlong Emperor]] (1735–1796). </gallery>
===Government seals=== [[Seal knob]] (紐刻) is an art that originated in ancient China and is mainly popular in East Asian countries. It focuses or decorates on the head-part or the top-side of a seal. It is a kind of sculpture or mini-sculpture. In China, the utmost important seal of all is the imperial seal called '[[He Shi Bi]]', now lost. It was said that the green jade took the form of a round shape with inscriptions that read "Having received the Mandate from Heaven, may (the emperor) lead a long and prosperous life." (受命於天，既壽永昌) This was said to be written by the Primer [[Li Si]] for [[Qin Shi Huang]] Zhao Zheng, the Augustus Emperor of The Chinese Empire.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="4"> File:Han Dynasty jade seal (governmental, officer).jpg|[[Seal knob|Knob of a governmental seal]], [[Western Han dynasty]]. </gallery>
===Ruyi=== {{main|Ruyi (scepter)}}
[[Ruyi (scepter)|Ruyi]] is a scepter that serves primarily as a decoration. Its history began in the [[Qing dynasty]] when Ruyi scepters were given to noted visitors of the emperor. Now, they're given as birthday presents. Ruyi is made of different materials, including porcelain and jade. The term Ruyi means "may your wish be granted" or "as you wish". The unusual shape is meant to imitate the shape of a stemmed lotus flower.<ref>[http://www.gotheborg.com/glossary/?http://www.gotheborg.com/glossary/data/ruyi.shtml ''Ruyi''] Gotheborg.com Retrieved 30 August 2012.</ref>
<gallery widths="200px" heights="200px" perrow="4"> File:Forbiddencitypic17.jpg|A gold ruyi carved with flowers. Qing dynasty (1644–1911). [[Palace Museum]], [[Beijing]]. File:HB-Ruyi.JPG|Ruyi scepter, Qing dynasty, 18th century, [[Übersee-Museum Bremen|Uberseemuseum]], [[Bremen]], [[Germany]] File:Ornament with persimmon, lily & ruyi fungus Asian Art Museum SF B65J5a-b.JPG|Ornament with persimmon, lily and ruyi fungus, chalcedony, 1900–49, Qing Dynasty or [[Taiwan after World War II|Republic Period]]. On display at the [[Asian Art Museum of San Francisco]]. </gallery>
